This paper uses natural language processing and search engines to automatically discover websites that are censored in China, which involves techniques related to information retrieval (IR) and computational linguistics (CL). Additionally, the paper discusses the development of a block list, which could fall under the categories of cybersecurity (CR) and social networking (SI). Finally, the paper touches on the cultural and political aspects of censorship in China, which could relate to the subfield of cultural computing (CY).
